Comparing Clinton and Trump ’ s Economic Policy: It ’ s all about the money
Investing in infrastructure and preventing the TTP is what both Clinton and Trump want.
But the two US presidential contenders disagree on tax and energy policy, as well as on a fundamental issue.
The difference in economic policy between Donald Trump and Hillary Clinton is fundamentally philosophical.
The, on the role of the state.
Trump wants to keep them small if in doubt and warns how the state can harm the economy - with taxes and regulations.
Clinton wants to tax the economy to death and regulate it to death, he says.
He himself, however, would be very different, Trump claims.
He said he would massively reduce regulations and advocate far-reaching tax reform with lower tax rates - for private individuals and for companies.
Clinton, on the other hand, says: the state has certain tasks to perform, it has disadvantaged opportunities to open up and needs money for this.
That is why taxes on the rich would be increased, she says.
Interestingly, both are very close to the issue of infrastructure.
Trump and Clinton say they must invest in them almost word for word.
The democratic candidate even announces the biggest investment in new jobs since the Second World War.
Government infrastructure investment programs are classic Democratic policies, and are strongly opposed by, say, the Republican wing ’ s critical Teaparty.
So Trump may face intra-party discussions.
The differences in energy and climate policy are clearer.
Trump wants to build coal-fired power plants and restart coal production in the US.
Oil extraction should also be possible in so far protected areas, he wants to cancel the Paris climate protection agreement.
Clinton, on the other hand, explicitly wants to expand renewable energies with her investment program and demands: "One country will become the superpower of clean energies and create millions of jobs."
"It will probably be either China, Germany or America - I want us to be."
But not only in terms of infrastructure - the two competitors are not too far apart in international trade agreements either.
Neither wants to sign the TPP, the Trans-Pacific Trade Agreement.
At the same time, they do not want to isolate the US from international trade - they simply want to protect American jobs better.
Clinton calls for them to be paid better.
The current minimum wage of 7.25 US dollars is a pittance.
She wants to raise it to 15 dollars per hour.
What Trump wants to do on this issue is not entirely clear: he says that the minimum wage must be raised, then he says that it must not be changed.
But the big discussion in the coming months is likely to revolve more around the tax policies of the two camps.
On the one hand, there is Trump, who wants to relieve the economy and citizens in order to boost growth.
His critics reproach him that this would only increase the budget deficit.
On the other side is Clinton, who wants at least the rich to pay more taxes, and whose critics say: more taxes are not the solution either.
Escape: "Every refugee woman has experiences of sexual violence"
For women fleeing alone, sexual violence is almost part of everyday life.
When they arrive in Germany, they are often traumatized.
A house offers refuge.
Four women sit in a large kitchen.
Each of them has a baby who is at most one year old.
One of them has put her little son in her arms.
He looks curiously into the room with big eyes.
His mother stares at the tabletop.
Until she realizes that she is being watched.
She smiles briefly and kisses the little one.
The scene seems normal.
Until you talk to Katrin Bahr.
She is the managing director of Condrobs, a provider of social assistance in Bavaria, and deals, among other things, with the topic of women on the run.
The four women in the kitchen are refugees.
They live in the north of Munich in one of the few decentralised accommodations for single women and their children in Bavaria.
In January, Condrobs opened the facility together with Pro Familia and the Münchner Frauenhilfe.
It was officially opened recently.
60 people live there - about 40 women and 20 children.
There are no men - not even as visitors.
The exception is a guard at the door.
"It is no exaggeration to say that every woman who arrives here has experienced sexual violence on her flight," says Bahr.
"Men flee because of wars, because they are politically persecuted, because they are threatened with torture or death, or because their families send them to Europe as bearers of hope," she says.
In the case of women, other reasons for fleeing predominate: "Many steal away secretly because they see no other way out."
In their homeland they have experienced sexual violence, forced marriages, honour killings, slavery or forced prostitution.
That drives them away.
On the run it goes on.
"It is not uncommon for tugs to demand a sexual act for a bottle of water, for example," says Bahr.
And the women are alone, they are not protected by their families.
Those who believe that the end will come as soon as they arrive in Germany are wrong, says Bahr.
Here, too, single women in refugee shelters would often be considered inferior and abused at worst.
As a result, approximately 90 percent of the women living in their accommodation in the north of Munich are traumatized, she estimates.
"Some of the children were certainly not born voluntarily".
Many women are so accustomed that they say nothing.
"Or they dare not speak openly about what they have experienced, because the shame is too great."
Since they often do not know how to help themselves, Bahr demands that they need more accommodation just for them.
In Bavaria, the seven district governments are responsible for housing refugees.
When asked whether they knew of a project similar to the one in Munich in their area of responsibility, some answered no.
In the Upper Palatinate and Upper Franconia, for example, there is no such thing in government accommodation.
Also in Swabia alone refugee women are not accommodated separately, say Karl Heinz Meyer, press speaker of the government.
In Upper Bavaria, Lower Franconia and Middle Franconia there are floors or houses for single women and their children.
The exception is Lower Bavaria, where there are two central accommodations exclusively for women.
The Committee on Women's Rights and Gender Equality in the European Parliament also calls for women to be housed separately from men.
According to a study published for the Committee, 'It is very important that men and women are housed separately'.
'If there is a lack of privacy or if men and women are accommodated together, there may be - more persistently - violence against women '.
Especially the washrooms should be separated and easily accessible for women, the study says.
How much the women feel this need for protection can be seen in the crowds that come to the house in Munich.
“Since word got around that we exist, we have a long waiting list, ” says Bahr.
One could easily open a second house.
