Community, spirit, health: Singing is good for seniors
The singing has accompanied Ursel Kipp all her life: As a young girl she was in the school choir, in the teacher's degree, she took the subject of music, and today the 78 Jahre sings in a senior choir.
"Singing moves me - emotionally and physically", she describes.
After a rehearsal she feels balanced, happy and altogether more alive, she says.
By the way, she does something good for her health and her spirit.
Because singing is from several perspectives a mad hobby for seniors, says Erhard Hackler of the German senior league.
Most seniors sing in a choir and share the joy of music with like-minded people, Hackler describes.
By the regular being together seniors can attach and maintain social contacts.
Because often social and family structures dissolve in old age, a choir is then an ideal opportunity to spend time with other people.
Ursel Kipp also had this experience in her choir: "To coordinate and organize oneself, to be able to rely on others and to learn from each other - a choir is a very special form of being together".
Singing can be exhausting in a positive sense, says Hackler.
Because seniors train deep and controlled breathing.
If you regularly require your lungs, you will not lose your breath so quickly in everyday life.
Even when it comes to maintaining the sound of the voice in old age, singing is an optimal hobby.
Singing often has a very special effect on older people, says Ursula Lenz from the Federal Association of Senior Citizens.
In the older generations, communal singing had a much higher value, it was part of everyday life, both in school and in leisure time, she explains.
Lenz frequently observes that singing or listening to songs awakens many memories in older people, often associated with positive feelings of their youth.
Through song lyrics and especially melodies, even people suffering from dementia remember events long ago.
When singing, the head is also required to perform a special feat, explains Lenz.
Concentrating on your own voice and a given rhythm at the same time and adapting to the other singers - that is a great cognitive challenge.
Elderly people, in particular, who live alone, practice not to concentrate solely on themselves.
Another positive aspect is the recognition one receives from singing in a choir, says Hackler.
An enthusiastic audience is a great praise.
Self-esteem also grows through singing in the choir.
To show oneself: If I practice for a long time, I become better and grow beyond myself - this experience strengthens.
So there are plenty of good reasons to start singing.
Anyone who wants to try out a new hobby should not hesitate - even if he thinks he has little talent, advises Lenz.
You don't sing alone - with 50 people singing, who hears a sound going wrong?
In the search for the suitable offer seniors have different possibilities, say Hackler.
If someone from the circle of acquaintances sings in a senior choir, one can simply join.
Many cities also offer overviews of the choirs in the area.
Whoever wishes to sing in a church choir can contact the congregation or the head of the church directly.
Many senior choirs can also be found on the internet.
If you do not have access to the Internet, you can ask your family, friends or neighbours for help when searching the Internet.
Who has desire to sing, should join absolutely a choir, guesses / advises Hackler.
Singing is good for the soul and has something liberating - this applies to all ages.
Cats are more sensitive than males to the cries of kittens
In Hannover, biologists have investigated the effect of calling cat babies on adult animals.
To their surprise, the meowing did not leave the males indifferent - however, they always behaved the same in contrast to the females.
Female cats can recognize the degree of excitement of cat babies by meowing of the little ones.
They react ten percent faster to the sounds of kittens who think they are in great need, as scientists from the Veterinary School and the Hannover Medical School (MHH) have discovered.
Males also react to the calls of kittens - but always the same.
"Obviously, the acoustic differences between the miaowing of less and strongly excited young animals are either imperceptible or insignificant for the males," said the biologist Wiebke Konerding from the MHH.
She is the lead author of the study, which was published this Friday in the journal "BMC Evolutionary Biology".
In a previous study, the research team had already found that the duration and pitch of the kittens ’ screams differ with the urgency of their need for help.
A total of nine adult males and eight females from the livestock of the MHH were observed.
On the one hand, calls were played to them by little ones, who were taken out of the litter box for three minutes and separated from their mother and siblings.
On the other hand, they were confronted with screams of more excited kittens, which were raised additionally.
The researchers consider their results to be meaningful despite the small sample.
"All females, even those who did not yet have their own offspring, reacted in a differentiated way to the screams," said Konerding.
They turned over faster to the loudspeaker, if this shouts of the very excited kittens played off.
This ability is possibly congenital or develops with sexual maturity.
"It was a surprise that the males reacted at all," said the biologist.
In the past, scientists have repeatedly investigated the reactions of men and women to baby sounds in humans.
Also some studies showed that women reacted more sensitively to infants, no matter whether they were already mothers or not, reported the biologist Marina Scheumann.
