Military leadership falsifies ISIS intelligence, Congressional Committee notes
Military personnel of the United States Central Command changed intelligence information in order to draw a more optimistic picture of the war against the so-called Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than the actual conditions on the ground would have allowed, reported a committee of inquiry of the Congress in a report on Thursday.
The preliminary report, prepared by a task force of Republican members of the Armed Forces Committee, Intelligence Committee, and Defense Budget Committee, reports deep discontent among Central Command intelligence analysts who reported how superiors changed their perceptions of America ’ s efforts in the fight against the Islamic State.
Central Command, Cencom for short, is the military headquarters in Tampa, Florida, which controls the American military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
"Intelligence information, typically emitted by high-ranking Centcom commanders, regularly gave a more positive picture of America's efforts against terrorism than actual conditions on the ground would have allowed, and was consistently more positive than analyses by other intelligence agencies," quoted a newspaper article.
"What happened at Centcom is unacceptable - our soldiers suffer when bad analyses are presented to our political leaders," noted Ken Calvert, Republican member of the House of Representatives.
The management errors in Centcom reach up to the top of the organization.
The ten-page report details consistent problems in 2014 and 2015 in the descriptions and analyses of America ’ s efforts to train Iraqi forces.
While there is no direct evidence that senior Obama officials have given orders to change the reports, it shows how analysts have faced pressure from their superiors to paint a more optimistic picture of the threat to the Islamic State, also known as ISIS or ISIL.
“During the first half of 2015, many Central Command press releases, statements and statements to Congress were significantly more positive than factual, ” the report noted.
For example, a Centcom member publicly announced that a military recapture of Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq ’ s second largest city, remains under the control of the Islamic State.
"After months of investigation, so much is clear," Mike Pompeo, Republican Congressman from Kansas, said in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, Central Command leaders modified intelligence reporting to minimize the danger posed by ISIS in Iraq.
The Republicans created the task force after it was leaked that analysts were worried about manipulating reports on the Islamic State.
The report published on Thursday will be supplemented by more detailed findings as the investigation continues.
In addition, further investigations by Centcom reports by the Inspector General of the Ministry of Defence are ongoing.
Democratic members of the Intelligence Committee released their own findings on Thursday, in line with some of the Republican Task Force ’ s conclusions.
“In 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an excessively restricted process for intelligence assessments of ISIL and the Iraqi security services, ” the senior Democrat on the committee, a member of the House of Representatives Adam B. Schiff, announced in a statement.
This process, according to Mr. Schiff, "delayed the publication of intelligence reports," damaged analysts' morale, and "gave excessively little room for dissent."
But Mr. Schiff and the Democrats stated that they had found no evidence of White House interference with Centcom analysts regarding a "certain political opinion."
The preliminary results of the Congressional investigation were published on Tuesday by "The Daily Beast".
Last August, the New York Times reported of investigations by the inspector general of the Pentagon, which were taken up after complaints by Centcom analysts.
According to Cmdr. Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, the Department of Defense would not comment on Congressional reports while the inspector general ’ s investigation was still ongoing.
But he also stated that "experts sometimes have divergent views on the interpretation of complex data, and that the intelligence services and the Ministry of Defense welcome a controversial discussion of these important issues of national defense."
The investigation has repercussions beyond the question of a successful American-led air campaign in Iraq and Syria (a claim now made by a growing number of Defense officials).
Last year ’ s accusations, however, raised the question of whether President Obama can rely on Central Command for honest assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya, and other crisis regions.
Criticism of secret information about the Islamic State is reminiscent of disagreements more than a decade ago, when a Centcom analyst, Gregory Hooker, wrote a paper about how George W. Bush ’ s administration, contrary to many analysts ’ recommendations, planned only a small occupying force in Iraq, spending little time worrying about the consequences of the 2003 invasion.
Mr. Hooker also played a key role in the uprising against the current reporting on the Islamic State.
Last year, according to government sources, Mr. Hooker ’ s team stated that, contrary to the government ’ s statements, air strikes against the refineries held by the Islamic State would not have a significant impact on the terrorist group ’ s financial situation, as they would have put provisional refineries into operation to sell oil on the black market.
However, this finding was not published, reported The Times in September.
Centcom's former commander, Gen. Lloyd J. Austin III, was criticized by members of the legislature for his overly positive assessment of the war situation at a hearing before the Senate.
General Austin retired in April and was replaced by Gen. Joseph L. Votel at Central Command.
