In the midst of the rage of the Olympic Games, the zen of the trampoline
Wherever you are, however late, they are the Olympic Games.
The events in Rio de Janeiro feel constant and inevitable, a raging relay race between competition and aspiration.
It is as if the Olympic torch itself were a burning staff, passed from crossbowman to swimmer to gymnast to triathlete.
You cannot turn on the TV, read a newspaper, or listen to your neighbor in the coffee shop queue without hearing about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky, or the quarrel between Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos.
And then there is Logan Dooley.
Dooley, who participates in the Olympic Games for the first time and is a swarm of women with dimples, could have been among these well-known names, which will be broadcast at prime time, built up by sponsors and feel-good team TV, advertising, if he were a swimmer, gymnast or even fencer.
But Dooley, 28, from Lake Forest, California, is fighting for gold in Olympic trampoline gymnastics.
The Olympic flame does not illuminate every event equally.
Further from the centre, partly in the shade, there are sports that are not generally accepted: air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, taekwondo.
We will always have the breaststroke and may it prevail for a long time.
But if I am humbly able to make arguments for my particular favourite, let me draw attention to the discreet charm of the trampoline.
Although trampoline jumping has been an Olympic event since 2000, when it made its debut in Sydney, it has been perceived so sparsely for the last 16 years that many of those I asked didn ’ t know it was an Olympic sport at all.
This could also be regional ignorance.
Although the USA sent athletes to the competition, it has never won a medal in trampoline jumping and until 2012 it had an athlete who made it to the final round.
The Chinese and the Russians tend to share the prices for the men and the Chinese and the Canadians the prices for the women.
Dong Dong from China and Rosie MacLennan from Canada will defend their gold medal from London this year.
The trampoline jumping has a certain outsider charm, partly because it sounds for the unenlightened ear more suitable for a clown school than for the Olympic Games.
At this point I should admit that I am not an expert, but just a grounded enthusiast.
It has humorous potential - the cartoon-like trembling of its never-ending impact - but also the grace of gymnastics and diving, the two sports it essentially combines.
The word "trampoline" comes from the Spanish word El Trampoline, which means "springboard".
Emerging winners jump on a giant trampoline, shoot up to 30 feet in the air and have to make a series of falling movements (spinning, pike and somersaults) before landing on their feet.
They are evaluated according to the official Olympic program according to execution, degree of difficulty and "flight time".
Thirty-two athletes from 17 countries, 16 men and 16 women, will compete in Rio.
The most common Olympic vector is straight ahead.
In their quest for gold, medal seekers must go further, faster, up and over, sometimes to the finish, sometimes back and forth, up and down on the playground.
They chase not only the finish line or the exit wall, but also another scornful goal in the television broadcast: that of the world or the Olympic record.
The purposeful pursuit is noble, admirable, even fanatic - and it is enough to move even a spectator to tears.
But it is also what I find somewhat tiring when watching these games.
The trampoline offers a breathing space.
The vector of the trampoline jumper is on top.
Moving forward is not the goal.
He or she bounces off, seemingly weightless like an astronaut, goes up, then down, then up again effortlessly.
Here, too, there is a competition, of course not without difficulty, but during the exercise there is no hectic attack on the target, no vault into the distance, only the dreamy, elegant suspension of time and gravity.
It is as Zen as the competition at the Olympics can only be.
The women ’ s qualifying and final rounds will take place on Friday afternoon, streaming at 13.00 Eastern Time; the men ’ s on Saturday, also at 13.00.
NBC will air the finals as part of an afternoon block on both days from 2pm.
In the midst of the Olympia mania, they promise a quiet, pleasant moment, one that is likely to be overlooked in the general turmoil.
If the only way to raise awareness is through the gazing and objectification of male athletes - as the US male gymnasts recently suggested in The Wall Street Journal - then Mr. Dooley awaits his new, vaporized following.
"A Generation Protesting" in Ethiopia, Long an Ally of the USA
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators calling for political change in Ethiopia met with violent opposition from the government.
Witnesses testify that dozens of protesters were killed in exchange of fire during clashes with the police.
Is Ethiopia about to collapse?
Over the past decade, it has been one of Africa ’ s most stable countries, a solid ally of the West with a fast-growing economy.
But, in recent months, anti-government protests have shaken the country and expanded to more and more areas.
Last week, thousands of people rushed into the streets demanding fundamental political changes.
The government's response was ruthless, according to human rights organisations.
Witnesses said that police shot and killed tens of unarmed demonstrators.
Videos circulating about the protests, presumably last year or early this year, show how security guards hit young people with sticks while forcing them to make a handstand against a wall.
The head of the UN Human Rights Agency is now demanding a thorough investigation.
"It has always been difficult to hold this country together and in the future it will be even more difficult," said Rashid Abdi, the Horn of Africa project leader of the International Crisis Group, a research group.
After Nigeria, Ethiopia is the most populous country in Africa and its stability is valued by the West.
American military and intelligence agencies are working closely with Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats beyond the region, particularly in Somalia. Few countries in Africa, if any, receive so much Western aid.
Ethiopia ’ s economy expanded at a respectable pace.
Its infrastructure has improved drastically - there is a new commuter train in the capital Addis Ababa.
The streets are generally quiet, safe and clean.
Although Ethiopia was anything but a model of democracy - human rights organisations have consistently led the government's repression - opposition in the country has been curtailed, effectively silencing dissidents.
Many were sent into exile or prison, killed or driven into the vastness of the desert.
But that could change.
“If you suppress people and they have no other options than to protest, it breaks out, ” said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer in Central Ethiopia.
The whole youth protested.
A generation is protesting.
There are numerous complaints covering everything from land use to the stranglehold on the ruling coalition ’ s power.
After a widely criticised election last year, the ruling party and its allies were given the last seat of the opposition and now control 100% of the parliament.
At the same time, tensions along the border with Eritrea are rising; a battle over this ragged, controversial line claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatists like the Oromo or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, which have been more or less defeated in recent years, could exploit the turbulence and rearm themselves.
Several factors explain why feelings of bitterness now explode beneath the surface after years of pre-simmering.
The first seems harmless: smartphones.
Only in recent years, many Ethiopians have been able to communicate through social media, as cheaper smartphones have become more common and Internet services have improved.
Even if the government blocks access to Facebook and Twitter, which it does at regular intervals, especially in protests, many people can still communicate over the Internet with proxies that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that they gathered to protest.
The second factor is that there is more solidarity between the Oromos and Amharas, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
The Oromos and Amharas are not natural enemies.
For eons, the Amharas, who come from Ethopia ’ s predominantly Christian highlands, have thrived in politics and economics, while exploiting the Oromos, many of whom are Muslims living in lowland areas.
But that, too, is changing.
"We are coordinating under one umbrella," said Mulatu Gemechu, a leader of the Oromos.
The largest protests took place in the Amhara and Oromos areas.
Many Amharas and Oromos feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, who make up about 6% of the population and dominate the military, intelligence, trade, and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Mr Meles, a former rebel leader, was Prime Minister of Ethiopia for 17 years until his death from an undisclosed disease in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could think around corners.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at seeing early signs of dissatisfaction and using special representatives to deal with opponents and render them harmless.
"The current regime lacks this basic skill," said Mr Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, has been chosen to take the position of Mr Meles for relatively obscure reasons.
Unlike Mr. Meles, who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Mr. Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say that he does not enjoy the confidence of the Tigray-controlled security services.
Many fear that the result will be more bloodshed.
The last time that Ethiopia experienced such an uproar was in 2005, after thousands protested against elections that, according to analysts, seemed to have been botched by the government and then stolen.
During the raids that followed, many protesters were killed, though less than in recent months, and that period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts praised Ethiopia ’ s leaders for their visionary infrastructure planning, such as the new commuter train, and for their measurable progress in reducing poverty.
But, evidently, this has not prevented the Ethiopian government ’ s internal resentment from intensifying.
And it is taking a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, an Amharic city, attacked Tigray-run businesses, and social media hatred of Tigrays is becoming more common.
Analysts say the protests put the US and other Western allies in a strange position.
The American government used Ethiopia as a base for drone flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently announced that it had closed that base.
