Rare sight.
Greenland sharks usually only come to the surface in winter.
This shark was allowed back into the sea after an investigation on board the research vessel Sanna.
He was born in 1624 and swims with a good 1 km / h through the North Atlantic - until today.
Greenland sharks only get offspring when they are 150 years old.
The Greenland shark swims leisurely along the bottom of the North Atlantic, in one hour it comes on average only 1,220 meters far.
Only when it matters, the five-meter-long animal accelerates to a full 2.6 km / h - and is half as fast as a seal with this top speed.
But this lifestyle of slowness seems to be a panacea for old age.
Julius Nielsen from the University of Copenhagen and his colleagues report in the journal "Science" about a Greenland shark that could be 392 years old.
"Insanity", comments Alexander Scheuerlein from the Max-Planck-Institute for Demographic Research in Rostock on this lifespan, which represents a world record for vertebrates.
The evolutionary biologist has long suspected that Greenland sharks are getting very old.
But the evidence was lacking.
Greenland sharks are difficult to observe as they live mainly in the Arctic Ocean off the sparsely populated coasts of Canada, Greenland, Norway and Spitsbergen.
Because they prefer water temperatures of around six degrees Celsius, they usually only appear on the surface in winter.
Researchers know little about the Greenland shark lifestyle.
They measured their slow motion speed when they equipped six animals with a transmitter off Spitsbergen.
These sharks still make prey: Researchers found the remains of a seal in an animal ’ s stomach, another had swallowed the jawbone of a young polar bear.
Possibly they hunt sleeping animals or patrol at the bottom of the ice sea and look for cadavers, that stagger from higher water-layers downward.
Julius Nielsen and his colleagues now studied 28 Greenland sharks that fishermen caught between 2010 and 2013 off Greenland or Spitsbergen as bycatch from the depths of the North Atlantic.
The smallest shark was just 81 centimeters long, while the largest measured 502 centimeters.
In order to determine the age of the sharks, they analyzed the lens nucleus of the sharks using the Carbon-14 method.
This center of the eye lens originates already before the birth of the sharks, the proteins contained in it are not renewed later any more.
The two smallest sharks had remarkably much carbon 14 in the lens core.
Their birth was thus supposed to be after the early 1960 ’ s, when nuclear weapons tests threw large amounts of this radioactive carbon into the atmosphere.
In the third smallest animal, measuring 220 centimetres in length, the lens core contained a small surplus of carbon 14 from the nuclear weapons tests, which is likely to have celebrated its 50th birthday in 2012.
All larger Greenland sharks, on the other hand, had in their lens core normal carbon-14 “quantities, which originate from cosmic rays in the atmosphere.
Indeed, the Carbon 14 Clock for a 393-centimeter Greenland shark showed an age of 335 years, while the record 502-centimeter shark should even be 392 years old.
It was known that Greenland sharks do not produce females until they are longer than four meters.
The researchers were now able to assign an age to the length.
Since one of the animals with 392 centimeters stood probably at the threshold to the sexually mature and its age with 156 years was determined, Greenland-sharks let themselves with the increase obviously at least one and a half centuries time.
This should also be the world record for vertebrates at the moment.
It is no coincidence that such methusalemes live mainly in icy waters.
The previous record holder, a 211-year-old Greenland whale with a 120-year-old harpoon tip on its neck, was also caught off Alaska.
Due to the low temperatures, the organism of the animals living there often runs on low flame.
They mature later - and age more slowly.
In order to keep warm in the cold water, the animals often become especially large.
Because the volume grows much faster than its surface, through which the animal loses heat.
The heat loss of one gram of mouse is therefore much greater than that of one gram of elephant.
Another advantage: You have fewer enemies.
"A smaller animal therefore lives more dangerously and should concentrate on having as many offspring as possible as soon as possible," explains the evolutionary biologist Scheuerlein.
A very large animal, on the other hand, should rather invest its resources in a long life.
