Data theft: hackers extort their ransom
Programmers of blackmail and malware are currently targeting companies - and are successful.
According to a recent survey of malware defence specialists Malwarebytes among 540 Companies in North America, Great Britain and Germany, 40 Percent of the companies surveyed in the past twelve months at least once, sometimes several times victim of an attack with blackmailer software.
In Germany, almost 20 percent of the companies were already the target of a ransomware, or extortion.
40 percent of the victims willingly paid the ransom demanded by the perpetrators in order to be able to use the attacked systems and data again.
The perpetrators are increasingly specializing their extortioners, according to the observations of Malwarebytes, in attacks on corporate networks.
If they are successful there, the potentially extorted ransom is much higher than with private users.
"We are currently observing an alarmingly rapid evolution of malware," explains Malwarebytes' boss Marcin Kleczynski in an interview with "Welt".
In 2008, most malware programs were designed to send advertisements.
Then, the culprits discovered blackmail and software for themselves.
At first, private users were the target, but the shift to corporate attacks has been frighteningly rapid in recent months.
Ransomware works according to a simple pattern: Once active on a victim ’ s computer, it searches specifically for recently modified files, such as Word, Excel, or database files, as well as for archives of images and videos.
These files encrypts the Ransomware and deletes the originals sustainably.
The software then presents the claims of the extortionists.
In order to get the encryption code to the files, victims must transfer money - mostly in the form of the cryptocurrency Bitcoin.
But where private users are concerned with their personal photo data base, companies are concerned with sensitive customer data or project data bases, without which production stops.
Accordingly, the damage is higher, if a Ransomware strikes.
22 percent of the affected German companies reported losses of sales due to ransomware, 13 percent even had to interrupt the business completely, in one case people were in mortal danger.
Several hospitals in Germany have already been the victims of attacks, whose patients may be acutely threatened by the loss of medical records.
"We always say to the victims: don't pay, you only promote the problem," Kleczynski explains.
But 80 to 90 percent of companies that pay get their data back.
It is difficult for managers to reject the perpetrators' demands in the face of a standstill in the company.
The hackers in turn know this and try everything to build up a good reputation.
In a recent study, the security researchers of F ’ Secure have examined the user interfaces and contact with the extortionists and come to the conclusion: The perpetrators are actually trying to establish a kind of customer service to earn more money.
They explain to their victims via chat, how they can pay by Bitcoin, set up freely accessible support, websites or decrypt free example, files.
And if private individuals are redeemed after payments of a few hundred euros, some companies will have to negotiate hard and pay five-digit sums to get their data back unencrypted.
In view of the potentially high and relatively risk-free profits from the ransomware, the hackers become increasingly professional and share the work, explains security expert Chester Wisniewski from the antivirus vendor Sophos: "A single person can write a ransomware approximately within a week."
It is more likely, however, that these are three or four people.
The programmers then sell their malicious software in the form of a software development kit to the actual blackmailers.
The previous malware ’ s kits were created by buying the malware itself, consulting and additional tools for a one-time, fixed price between $1000 and $10,000.
"The scope of delivery includes a customization tool so that smaller configurations, appearance and branding can be changed," says Wisniewski.
The blackmailers then look for further hackers to spread the freshly bought software among the victims.
We live in a service economy.
You log into one of the underground forums, buy the set from a criminal and ask another to install the software on as many PCs as possible.
Payment is made per infected computer.
“Usually the criminals then assign spammers with the spreading ”, explains Wisniewski.
The risk of Ransomware is now known to many companies, who secure their data better.
More than 50 percent of the companies in charge of IT in the Malwarebytes “Survey ” trust to be able to fend off ransomware using file“ back ups ” and scanner software.
Accordingly, the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies.
"If the encryption of data alone is no longer a sufficient threat to successful execution, the perpetrators instead threaten to publish sensitive data such as customer lists or price calculations," explains Malwarebytes' head Marcin Kleczynski.
Depending on the type of data, the damage potential is thus many times higher than before.
The perpetrators could also target completely new targets on the Internet of Things in the future.
At the Defcon hacker conference, security researchers demonstrated how they could get an Internet-connected thermostat under their control.
In the middle of winter, the activation of such a blocked heater could well be worth a ransom for some victims.
If the culprits then block instead of the heating in the future an entire production line in a factory, Ransomware could also become an issue in Industry 4.0.
