Old buildings, a few lime trees, in between a remnant of cobblestones: The Rigaer Street in Berlin, Friedrichshain does not seem so at first glance, but the police considers it one of the "dangerous places" of the city.
If you walk along the road from east to west, you will pass playgrounds, a freshly painted kindergarten and an organic food shop.
Someone sprayed "ugly!" on the façade of a grey house.
Opposite a Lidl, which is soon to be demolished, construction is already underway: By 2017, a house with high windows and 133 new rental apartments is to be built here.
However, articles about this "trendy district", as the real estate company responsible calls Friedrichshain, have been preferably illustrated with burning cars in recent weeks.
The reason is the house with the number 94: Once it was occupied, now the residents have leases, but on the ground floor are still occupied rooms and are used for events.
Especially the Berlin Senator for Interior Affairs Henkel had since the beginning of the year several times in favor of a tough action by the police against the project, the area as a "No-Go-Zone" for police officers and the 94 called the starting point of autonomous violence.
After the rooms on the ground floor, the Kadterschmiede, with 300 police officers were evacuated on June 22, the police officially patrolled with 30 to 40 officers and three crew cars on site for three weeks, cordoned off parts of the street and prevented visitors from entering the house with number 94.
In the meantime, the rooms were renovated by construction workers on behalf of the unknown homeowners.
On July 13, an administrative court in Berlin ruled that the eviction had been illegal, and a day later, police and construction workers left to the cheers of sympathizers and residents.
On this summer afternoon, the street seems peaceful: parents go for a walk with children, people sit on the sidewalk in front of the houses in the sun, others talk before late hours.
In the immediate vicinity of the housing projects are a primary school and kindergartens.
Left violence is not the main concern of many residents: Kerstin Neugebauer, who has lived in the neighbourhood since 1999, and Jana *, who raises three children here, are particularly annoyed by the police presence.
With the inhabitants of the house projects they share the concern before rising rents and gentrification.
It does not sound like a neighborhood that mostly wanted police protection from vandalizing leftists.
The ditch opened by the Berlin Senator for the Interior and the police between squatters and their neighbors obviously does not exist.
Friedrichshain in the east of Berlin was actually a traditional working-class district, which even today has a low average income and a high risk of poverty compared to the rest of the city.
The squatting of buildings and the resulting housing projects have also long been part of the neighbourhood: in 1990, numerous buildings in the former GDR were occupied, including almost the entire Mainzer Strasse near the Riga people.
While the people of Mainz were evicted in a regular street battle, many of the projects in the Riga area were legalized and are still partly inhabited by the people who occupied them 26 years ago.
At the same time, in recent years, the district has increasingly become a magnet for tourists and Berliners who choose to live in Berlin from all over the world.
This is also reflected in rents, which have increased by almost 60 percent in new rentals since 2009.
Many of the new buildings in the Riga region are attacked as symbols of this development: they are recognizable by discs thrown in or freshly painted facades that have been pelted with bags of paint.
No other road was mentioned so often this year together with the words "left-autonomous violence".
One reason that not all neighbours see this as a problem may be that they are not necessarily affected by crime: according to statistics, crimes such as assault are directed almost exclusively at police officers.
Most of the crimes are property damage, which tends to affect new buildings and newly renovated houses.
For Kerstin Neugebauer, who has lived in a tenement building next to the controversial 94 for 17 years, there can be no question of insecurity.
As far as acts of violence are concerned, it is reassuring: the people in 94 are their neighbours, they certainly were not.
Also the famous burning cars do not exist directly in the Riga for a long time.
For the studied architect, her street is not a criminal focal point, on the contrary: "Here you help each other, live together on the street and get more from each other than anywhere else."
Neugebauer has deliberately moved into Rigaer Straße - and remained so.
That is why it was so important to her that the residents get their street back: from the police, the politicians and the media, who all suddenly claimed the authority to interpret the district in July.
But in the eyes of residents such as Neugebauer, the street continues to be taken away from them by faceless new buildings in former vacancies, which displace the old inhabitants.
"After all, these are condominiums that are not interesting for many people here - people who are not so well-heeled live here," she says.
"I absolutely cannot approve of violence and destruction."
